Copy constructor in Base class vs Derived class

Copy Constructor in Derived Class:
	If the derived class does not have a copy constructor that accepts a reference to a base class object, 
	attempting to copy a base class object to a derived class object will result in a compiler error. 

	The compiler needs an appropriate constructor to handle the conversion.

Copy Constructor in Base Class:
	If the base class does not have a copy constructor that accepts a reference to a derived class object, 
	but you try to copy a derived class object to the base class, it will still work. 
	This is because the derived class object can be implicitly converted to the base class type, 
	and the base class copy constructor will handle the copying of the base class part of the derived class object.
